  "doc_id": "21889",
  "text": "The research effort thus far has established that, in obesity, the expanding adipose tissue makes a substantial contribution to the development of obesity-linked inflammation via the secretion of various proinflammatory cytokines, chemokines and adipokines. Recent investigations into the mechanisms responsible for this phenomenon have outlined a role for the macrophage [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In fact, macrophage accumulation in adipose tissue is positively correlated with adipocyte size and contributes to the expression of proinflammatory mediators of insulin resistance, such as TNF-α, IL-6 and inducible nitric oxide synthase (iNOS) [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Furthermore, both inhibition of macrophage function, via myeloid-specific IκB kinase-β deletion [CITATION_6] , and prevention of macrophage accumulation in adipose tissue, via deletion of C-C motif chemokine receptor-2 [CITATION_7] , prevent the development of the inflammatory phenotype and insulin resistance with obesity. Hence, there is growing support for the current notion that macrophage infiltration into adipose tissue is central to obesity-related metabolic disorders.",
